on | first3 = Marco | year = 2006 | title = Bio-char Sequestration in Terrestrial Ecosystems \u2013 A Review | url = http://www.garnautreview.org.au/CA25734E0016A131/WebObj/d07119990GeneralSubmission-DepartmentofAgricultureandFoodWA-Lehmann__2006_char_review/$File/d07%20119990%20General%20Submission%20-%20Department%20of%20Agriculture%20and%20Food%20WA%20%20-%20Lehmann__2006_char_review.pdf | journal = Mitigation and Adaptation Strategies for Global Change | volume = 11 | issue = 2 | pages = 395\u2013427 | doi = 10.1007/s11027-005-9006-5 | display-authors = etal | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20080722193929/http://www.garnautreview.org.au/CA25734E0016A131/WebObj/d07119990GeneralSubmission-DepartmentofAgricultureandFoodWA-Lehmann__2006_char_review/%24File/d07%20119990%20General%20Submission%20-%20Department%20of%20Agriculture%20and%20Food%20WA%20%20-%20Lehmann__2006_char_review.pdf | archivedate = 22 July 2008| citeseerx = 10.1.1.183.1147 }}\n* Nakka, S. B. R. (2011) [http://www.biochar-international.org/Sustainability_Biochar_Systems_DevelopingCountries \"Sustainability of biochar systems in developing countries\"], Published in IBI\n* {{cite magazine|url=https://www.newscientist.com/article/mg20126921.500-one-last-chance-to-save-mankind.html?full=true\n| title=One last chance to save mankind |date=3 January 2009 |first=Gaia |last=Vince |issue=2692 |magazine=[[New Scientist]] |ref=harv}}\n\n* {{cite journal | last1 = Woolf | first1 = Dominic | last2 = Amonette | first2 = James E. | last3 = Street-Perrott | first3 = F. Alayne | last4 = Lehmann | first4 = Johannes | last5 = Joseph | first5 = Stephen | year = 2010 | title = Sustainable biochar to mitigate global climate change | journal = Nature Communications | volume = 1 | issue = 5| pages = 1\u20139 | doi=10.1038/ncomms1053 | pmid=20975722 | pmc=2964457| bibcode = 2010NatCo...1E..56W }}\n* Graber, E.R. and Elad, Y. (2013) Biochar Impact on Plant Resistance to Disease. Chapter 2, In Biochar and Soil Biota, Ed. Natalia Ladygina, CRC Press, Boca Raton, Florida, pp.&nbsp;41\u201368\n* {{cite journal | last1 = Ameloot | first1 = N. | last2 = Graber | first2 = E.R. | last3 = Verheijen | first3 = F. | last4 = De Neve | first4 = S. | year = 2013 | title = Effect of soil organisms on biochar stability in soil: Review and research needs | journal = Eur. J. Soil Science | volume = 64 | issue = 4| pages = 379\u2013390 | doi=10.1111/ejss.12064}}\n* {{cite journal | last1 = Jeffery | first1 = S. | last2 = Verheijen | first2 = F.G.A. | last3 = van der Velde | first3 = M. | last4 = Bastos | first4 = A.C. | year = 2011 | title = A quantitative review of the effects of biochar application to soils on crop productivity using meta-analysis | url = https://zenodo.org/record/3414237| journal = Agriculture, Ecosystems & Environment | volume = 144 | pages = 175\u2013187 | doi=10.1016/j.agee.2011.08.015}}\n* {{cite journal | last1 = Hernandez-Soriano| first1 = M.C. | last2 = Kerre| first2 = B. | last3 = Goos| first3 = P. | last4 = Hardy| first4 = B. | last5 = Dufey| first5 = J. | last6 = Smolders| first6 = E. | year = 2015 | title = Long-term effect of biochar on the stabilization of recent carbon: soils with historical inputs of charcoal | journal = GCB Bioenergy | volume = 8 | issue = 2 | pages = 371\u2013381 | doi=10.1111/gcbb.12250| url = https://lirias.kuleuven.be/bitstream/123456789/492593/3/gcbb12250.pdf }}\n* {{cite journal | last1 = Hernandez-Soriano| first1 = M.C. | last2 = Kerre| first2 = B. | last3 = Kopittke | first3 = P. | last4 = Horemans | first4 = B. | last5 = Smolders | first5 = E. | year = 2016 | title = Biochar affects carbon composition and stability in soil: a combined spectroscopy-microscopy study | journal = Scientific Reports | volume = 6 | pages = 25127 | doi=10.1038/srep25127| pmid = 27113269 | pmc = 4844975 | bibcode = 2016NatSR...625127H }}\n* {{cite journal | last1 = Kerre| first1 = B. | last2 = Hernandez-Soriano| first2 = M.C. | last3 = Smolders| first3 = E. | year = 2016 | title = Partitioning of carbon sources among functional pools to investigate short-term priming effects of biochar in soil: a 13C study | journal = Science of the Total Environment | volume = 547 | pages = 30\u201338 | doi=10.1016/j.scitotenv.2015.12.107| pmid = 26780129 | bibcode = 2016ScTEn.547...30K}}\n* {{cite journal| first1= Manoj|last1= Tripathi|first2= J.N.|last2= Sabu|first3= P.|last3= Ganesan|title= Effect of process parameters on production of biochar from biomass waste through pyrolysis: A review|journal= Renewable and Sustainable Energy Reviews|volume= 55|date= 21 November 2015|pages= 467\u2013481|issn=1364-0321|doi= 10.1016/j.rser.2015.10.122}}\n* {{cite journal|first1=Kathrin|last1=Weber|first2=Peter|last2=Quicker|title=Properties of biochar|journal=Fuel|volume=217|date=1 April 2018|pages=240\u2013261|issn=0016-2361|doi=10.1016/j.fuel.2017.12.054}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{sisterlinks|d=Q905495|wikt=biochar|c=Category:Biochar|b=no|v=no|voy=no|n=no|mw=no|m=no|s=no|species=no|q=no}}\n{{Scholia|topic}}\n* [http://www.biochar-international.org International Biochar Initiative]\n* [https://www.biochar-us.org Biochar-us.org]\n\n{{Forestry}}\n{{Wood products}}\n{{deforestation and desertification}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Carbon capture and sequestration]]\n[[Category:Charcoal]]\n[[Category:Environmental soil science]]\n[[Category:Soil improvers]]\n[[Category:Wildfire ecology]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Lightweight black residue, made of carbon and ashes, after pyrolysis of biomass}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2020}}\n[[File:Biochar.jpg|thumb|alt=A hand holding a piece of biochar with a bucket of it in the background|A piece of biochar]]\n[[File:Biochar sample size.jpg|alt=Small pellets of biochar|thumb|Smaller pellets of biochar]]\n[[File:Biochar pile.jpg|alt=A large pile of biochar|thumb|Biochar after production, in a large pile]]\n'''Biochar''' is [[charcoal]] used as a [[Soil conditioner|soil amendment]] for both carbon sequestration and soil health benefits. Biochar is a stable solid, rich in [[carbon]], and can endure in soil for thousands of years.<ref name=indep1/> Like most charcoal, biochar is made from [[biomass]] via [[pyrolysis]]. Biochar is under investigation as a viable approach for [[carbon sequestration]],<ref name=indep1>{{cite news|work=[[The Independent]] |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/environment/climate-change/ancient-skills-could-reverse-global-warming-1055700.html |title=Ancient skills 'could reverse global warming' |first=Geoffrey |last=Lean |date=7 December 2008 |accessdate=1 October 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110913052413/http://www.independent.co.uk/environment/climate-change/ancient-skills-could-reverse-global-warming-1055700.html |archivedate=13 September 2011 }}</ref> as it has the potential to help [[Climate change mitigation|mitigate global warming]] and [[climate change]].<ref>Balal Yousaf, Guijian Liu, Ruwei Wang, Qumber Abbas, Muhammad Imtiaz, Ruijia Liu: Investigating the biochar effects on C-mineralization and sequestration of carbon in soil compared with conventional amendments using stable isotope (\u03b413C) approach. GCB Bioenergy 2016; {{DOI|10.1111/gcbb.12401}}</ref><ref name=RoyalSociety>{{cite web\n  |title=Geoengineering the climate: science, governance and uncertainty\n  |url=http://royalsociety.org/Geoengineering-the-climate/\n  |publisher=[[The Royal Society]]\n  |year=2009\n  |accessdate=22 August 2010\n}}</ref><ref name=\"DOI10.1038/ncomms1053\">\n{{cite journal\n| author = Dominic Woolf\n| author2 = James E. Amonette\n| author3 = F. Alayne Street-Perrott\n| author4 = Johannes Lehmann\n| author5 = Stephen Joseph\n|date=August 2010\n| title = Sustainable biochar to mitigate global climate change\n| journal = Nature Communications\n| volume = 1\n| issue = 5\n| pages = 56\n| doi = 10.1038/ncomms1053\n| pmid =20975722\n|issn=2041-1723\n| bibcode = 2010NatCo...1E..56W\n| pmc=2964457}}\n</ref> It results from processes related to [[pyrogenic carbon capture and storage]] (PyCCS).<ref>Constanze Werner, Hans-Peter Schmidt, Dieter Gerten, Wolfgang Lucht und Claudia Kammann (2018). Biogeochemical potential of biomass pyrolysis systems for limiting global warming to 1.5&nbsp;\u00b0C. [[Environmental Research Letters]], 13(4), 044036. https://doi.org/10.1088/1748-9326/aabb0e</ref>\n\nBiochar may increase [[soil fertility]] of [[acidic soil]]s (low pH soils), increase agricultural productivity, and provide protection against some foliar and soil-borne diseases.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.biochar.org/joomla/index2.php?option=com_content&do_pdf=1&id=24 |title= Slash and Char |accessdate=19 September 2014}}</ref> Regarding its definition in production, biochar is defined by the International Biochar Initiative as \"The solid material obtained from the thermochemical conversion of biomass in an oxygen-limited environment\".<ref>{{cite web\n|title=Standardized production definition and product testing guidelines for biochar that is used in soil\n|url=https://www.biochar-international.org/wp-content/uploads/2018/04/IBI_Biochar_Standards_V2.1_Final.pdf\n|year=2015\n|accessdate=23 November 2015\n}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\nThe word \"biochar\" is a late 20th Century English neologism derived from the [[Greek Language|Greek]] word {{lang|grc|[[wikt:\u03b2\u03af\u03bf\u03c2|\u03b2\u03af\u03bf\u03c2]]}}, ''bios'', \"[[life]]\" and \"[[char]]\" (product of carbonisation of biomass, as [[charcoal]]).<ref>{{Cite OED | biochar }}</ref> it is simply charcoal, but used in certain applications.\n\n[[Pre-Columbian era|Pre-Columbian]] [[Amazon rainforest|Amazonian]]s produced biochar by [[smolder]]ing agricultural waste (i.e., covering burning biomass with soil)<ref>Solomon, Dawit, Johannes Lehmann, Janice Thies, Thorsten Schafer, Biqing Liang, James Kinyangi, Eduardo Neves, James Petersen, Flavio Luizao, and Jan Skjemstad, ''Molecular signature and sources of biochemical recalcitrance of organic carbon in Amazonian Dark Earths'', 71 Geochemica et cosmochemica ACTA 2285, 2286 (2007) (\"Amazonian Dark Earths (ADE) are a unique type of soils apparently developed between 500 and 9000 years B.P. through intense anthropogenic activities such as biomass-burning and high-intensity nutrient depositions on pre-Columbian Amerindian settlements that transformed the original soils into Fimic Anthrosols throughout the Brazilian Amazon Basin.\") (internal citations omitted)</ref> in pits or trenches.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\">{{harvnb|Lehmann|2007a|pp=381\u2013387}} Similar soils are found, more scarcely, elsewhere in the world.  To date, scientists have been unable to completely reproduce the beneficial growth properties of ''terra preta''. It is hypothesized that part of the alleged benefits of ''terra preta'' require the biochar to be aged so that it increases the cation exchange capacity of the soil, among other possible effects. In fact, there is no evidence natives made biochar for soil treatment, but rather for transportable fuel charcoal; there is little evidence for any hypothesis accounting for the frequency and location of terra preta patches in Amazonia. Abandoned or forgotten charcoal pits left for centuries were eventually reclaimed by the forest. In that time, the initially harsh negative effects of the char (high pH, extreme ash content, salinity) wore off and turned positive as the forest soil ecosystem saturated the charcoals with nutrients. ''supra'' note 2 at 386 (\"Only aged biochar shows high cation retention, as in Amazonian Dark Earths. At high temperatures (30\u201370&nbsp;\u00b0C), cation retention occurs within a few months. The production method that would attain high CEC in soil in cold climates is not currently known.\") (internal citations omitted).</ref> It is not known if they intentionally used biochar to enhance soil productivity<ref name=\"ReferenceA\"/> European settlers called it ''[[Terra preta|terra preta de Indio]]''.<ref>{{harvnb|Glaser|Lehmann|Zech|2002|pp=219\u2013220}} \"These so-called Terra Preta do Indio (Terra Preta) characterize the settlements of pre-Columbian Indios. In Terra Preta soils large amounts of black C indicate a high and prolonged input of carbonized organic matter probably due to the production of charcoal in hearths, whereas only low amounts of charcoal are added to soils as a result of forest fires and slash-and-burn techniques.\" (internal citations omitted)</ref> Following observations and experiments, a research team working in [[French Guiana]] hypothesized that the Amazonian [[earthworm]] ''[[Pontoscolex corethrurus]]'' was the main agent of fine powdering and incorporation of charcoal debris in the mineral soil.<ref>{{cite journal |author1=Jean-Fran\u00e7ois Ponge |author2=St\u00e9phanie Topoliantz |author3=Sylvain Ballof |author4=Jean-Pierre Rossi |author5=Patrick Lavelle |author6=Jean-Marie Betsch |author7=Philippe Gaucher |year=2006 |title=Ingestion of charcoal by the Amazonian earthworm ''Pontoscolex corethrurus'': a potential for tropical soil fertility |journal=Soil Biology and Biochemistry |volume=38 |issue=7 |pages=2008\u20132009 |doi=10.1016/j.soilbio.2005.12.024 |url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/44735820 |format=PDF}}</ref>\n\n== Production ==\nBiochar is a high-carbon, fine-grained residue that is currently produced through modern [[pyrolysis]] processes; it is the direct [[thermal decomposition]] of biomass in the absence of [[oxygen]] (preventing [[combustion]]), which produces a mixture of solids (the biochar proper), liquid ([[Pyrolysis oil|bio-oil]]), and gas ([[syngas]]) products. The specific yield from [[pyrolysis]] is dependent on process condition, such as [[temperature]], [[residence time]], and heating rate.<ref>{{cite journal\n| first1= Manoj|last1= Tripathi|first2= J.N.|last2= Sabu|first3= P.|last3= Ganesan|title= Effect of process parameters on production of biochar from biomass waste through pyrolysis: A review|journal= Renewable and Sustainable Energy Reviews|volume= 55|date= 21 November 2015|pages= 467\u2013481|issn=1364-0321|doi= 10.1016/j.rser.2015.10.122}}</ref> These parameters can be optimized to produce either energy or biochar.<ref>{{harvnb|Gaunt|Lehmann|2008|pp=4152, 4155}} (\"Assuming that the energy in syngas is converted to electricity with an efficiency of 35%, the recovery in the life cycle energy balance ranges from 92 to 274&nbsp;kg CO<sub>2</sub> MWn<sup>\u22121</sup> of electricity generated where the pyrolysis process is optimized for energy and 120 to 360&nbsp;kg {{co2}} MWn<sup>\u22121</sup> where biochar is applied to land. This compares to emissions of 600\u2013900&nbsp;kg {{chem|CO|2}} MWh<sup>\u22121</sup> for fossil-fuel-based technologies.)</ref> Temperatures of {{convert|400|-|500|C|K}} produce more [[char]], whereas temperatures above {{convert|700|C|K}} favor the yield of liquid and gas fuel components.<ref name=Winsley1>{{cite journal\n| last=Winsley |first=Peter |title=Biochar and bioenergy production for climate change mitigation |volume=64\n| journal=[[New Zealand Science Review]]|year=2007}} (See Table 1 for differences in output for Fast, Intermediate, Slow, and Gasification).</ref> Pyrolysis occurs more quickly at the higher temperatures, typically requiring seconds rather than hours. The increasing heating rate will also lead to a decrease of pyrolysis biochar yield, while the temperature is in the range of {{convert|350|-|600|C|K}}.<ref>{{cite journal| first1= Tevfik|last1= Aysu|first2= M. Ma\u015fuk|last2= K\u00fc\u00e7\u00fck|title= Biomass pyrolysis in a fixed-bed reactor: Effects of pyrolysis parameters on product yields and characterization of products|journal= Energy|volume= 64|issue =1|date= 16 December 2013|pages= 1002\u20131025|issn=0360-5442|doi= 10.1016/j.energy.2013.11.053}}</ref> Typical yields are 60% [[bio-oil]], 20% biochar, and 20% syngas. By comparison, slow pyrolysis can produce substantially more char (\u224835%);<ref name=Winsley1/> this contributes to the observed soil fertility of [[terra preta]]. Once initialized, both processes produce net energy. For typical inputs, the energy required to run a \"fast\" pyrolyzer is approximately 15% of the energy that it outputs.<ref>{{harvnb|Laird|2008|pp=100, 178\u2013181}} \"The energy required to operate a fast pyrolyzer is \u223c15% of the total energy that can be derived from the dry biomass. Modern systems are designed to use the syngas generated by the pyrolyzer to provide all the energy needs of the pyrolyzer.\"</ref> Modern pyrolysis plants can use the syngas created by the pyrolysis process and output 3\u20139 times the amount of energy required to run.<ref name=ReferenceA/>\n\nBesides pyrolysis, [[torrefaction]] and [[hydrothermal carbonization]] process can also thermally decompose biomass to the solid material. However, these products cannot be strictly defined as biochar. The carbon product from the [[torrefaction]] process still contains some volatile organic components, thus its properties are between that of biomass feedstock and biochar.<ref>{{cite journal| first1= Harpreet Singh|last1= Kambo|first2= Animesh|last2= Dutta|title= A comparative review of biochar and hydrochar in terms of production, physicochemical properties and applications|journal= Renewable and Sustainable Energy Reviews|volume= 45|date= 14 February 2015|pages= 359\u2013378|issn=1364-0321|doi= 10.1016/j.rser.2015.01.050}}</ref> Furthermore, even the hydrothermal carbonization could produce a carbon-rich solid product, the [[hydrothermal carbonization]] is evidently different from the conventional thermal conversion process.<ref>{{cite book |first1 = Jechan| last1 = Lee| first2 = Ajit K.| last2 = Sarmah| first3 = Eilhann E.| last3 = Kwon | title = Biochar from biomass and waste - Fundamentals and applications | url = https://www.sciencedirect.com/book/9780128117293/biochar-from-biomass-and-waste |year = 2019| publisher = Elsevier | pages = 1\u2013462 | isbn = 978-0-12-811729-3| doi = 10.1016/C2016-0-01974-5| hdl = 10344/443}}</ref> Therefore, the solid product from [[hydrothermal carbonization]] is defined as \"hydrochar\" rather than \"biochar\".\n\nThe Amazonian pit/trench method<ref name=\"ReferenceA\"/> harvests neither bio-oil nor syngas, and releases a large amount of {{CO2}}, [[black carbon]], and other [[greenhouse gas]]es (GHGs) (and potentially, [[toxin]]s) into the air, though less greenhouse gasses than captured during the growth of the biomass. Commercial-scale systems process agricultural waste, paper byproducts, and even municipal waste and typically eliminate these side effects by capturing and using the liquid and gas products.  The production of biochar as an output is not a priority in most cases.\n\n=== Centralized, decentralized, and mobile systems ===\nIn a centralized system, all biomass in a region is brought to a central plant (i.e. [[Thermal power station#Types of thermal energy|biomass-fueled thermal power station]]<ref name=\"renewableenergyworld.com\">[https://www.renewableenergyworld.com/articles/2011/10/could-biomass-technology-help-commercialize-biochar.html Could Biomass Technology Help Commercialize Biochar?]</ref>) for processing into biochar. Alternatively, each farmer or group of farmers can operate a lower-tech [[kiln]]. Finally, a truck equipped with a pyrolyzer can move from place to place to pyrolyze biomass. Vehicle power comes from the [[syngas]] stream, while the biochar remains on the farm. The [[biofuel]] is sent to a refinery or storage site. Factors that influence the choice of system type include the cost of transportation of the liquid and solid byproducts, the amount of material to be processed, and the ability to feed directly into the power grid.\n\nThe most common crops used for making biochar include various tree species, as well as various [[energy crop]]s. Some of these energy crops (ie [[Pennisetum purpureum|Napier grass]]) can also store much more carbon on a shorter timespan than trees do.<ref>[http://www.cropj.com/meneze_10_9_2016_1297_1305.pdf Napier grass can produce 60 tonnes of CO2/ha]</ref>\n\nFor crops that are not exclusively for biochar production, the [[Residue-to-Product Ratio (RPR)]] and the collection factor (CF) the percent of the residue not used for other things, measure the approximate amount of feedstock that can be obtained for pyrolysis after harvesting the primary product. For instance, [[Brazil]] harvests approximately 460 million tons (MT) of [[sugarcane]] annually,<ref>{{cite web | publisher=FAOSTAT | year=2006 | url=http://faostat.fao.org/site/567/DesktopDefault.aspx?PageID=567 | accessdate=1 July 2008 | title=Production Quantity Of Sugar Cane In Brazil In 2006 | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150906230329/http://faostat.fao.org/site/567/DesktopDefault.aspx?PageID=567 | archivedate=6 September 2015 | df=dmy-all }}</ref> with an RPR of 0.30, and a CF of 0.70 for the sugarcane tops, which normally are burned in the field.<ref>Perera, K.K.C.K., P.G. Rathnasiri, S.A.S. Senarath, A.G.T. Sugathapala, S.C. Bhattacharya, and P. Abdul Salam, ''Assessment of the sustainable energy potential of non-plantation biomass resources in Sri'' Lanka, 29 Biomass & Bioenergy 199, 204 (2005) (showing RPRs for numerous plants, describing method for determining available agricultural waste for energy and char production).</ref> This translates into approximately 100 MT of residue annually, which could be pyrolyzed to create energy and soil additives. Adding in the [[bagasse]] (sugarcane waste) (RPR=0.29 CF=1.0), which is otherwise burned (inefficiently) in boilers, raises the total to 230 MT of pyrolysis feedstock. Some plant residue, however, must remain on the soil to avoid increased costs and emissions from nitrogen fertilizers.<ref>{{harvnb|Laird|2008|pp= 179}} \"Much of the current scientific debate on the harvesting of biomass for bioenergy is focused on how much can be harvested without doing too much damage.\"</ref>\n\nPyrolysis technologies for processing loose and leafy biomass produce both biochar and syngas.<ref>{{cite journal\n| first1=Rajeev |last1=Jorapur |first2=Anil K.|last2= Rajvanshi\n| doi=10.1016/S0961-9534(97)00014-7  |title=Sugarcane leaf-bagasse gasifier for industrial heating applications\n| journal=Biomass and Bioenergy |volume=13 |issue=3 |pages=141\u2013146 |year=1997}}</ref>\n\n=== Thermo-catalytic depolymerization ===\n\nAlternatively, \"thermo-catalytic depolymerization\", which utilizes [[Dielectric heating|microwave]]s, has recently been used to efficiently convert organic matter to biochar on an industrial scale, producing \u224850% char.<ref>{{cite journal\n| first1= Selhan|last1= Karag\u00f6z|first2= Thallada|last2= Bhaskar|first3= Akinori|last3= Muto|first4= Yusaku|last4= Sakata|first5= Toshiyuki|last5= Oshiki|first6= Tamiya|last6= Kishimoto|title= Low-temperature catalytic hydrothermal treatment of wood biomass: analysis of liquid products|journal= Chemical Engineering Journal|volume= 108|issue= 1\u20132|date= 1 April 2005|pages= 127\u2013137|issn=1385-8947\n|doi= 10.1016/j.cej.2005.01.007}}</ref><ref>{{cite news\n| url=https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2009/mar/13/charcoal-carbon\n| title='Biochar' goes industrial with giant microwaves to lock carbon in charcoal\n| first=Alok |last=Jha\n| newspaper=The Guardian\n| date=13 March 2009 |accessdate=23 September 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Properties==\nThe physical and chemical properties of biochars as determined by feedstocks and technologies are crucial for the application of biochars in the industry and environment. Different characterization data are employed to biochars and determine their performances in a specific use. For example, the guidelines published by the International Biochar Initiative provide standardized methods in evaluating the product quality of biochar for soil application.<ref>{{cite web\n|title=Standardized production definition and product testing guidelines for biochar that is used in soil\n|url=https://www.biochar-international.org/wp-content/uploads/2018/04/IBI_Biochar_Standards_V2.1_Final.pdf\n|year=2015\n|accessdate=23 November 2015\n}}</ref> The properties of biochar can be characterized in several respects, including the proximate and elemental composition, pH value, porosity etc., which correlate with different biochar properties. The atomic ratios of biochar, including H/C and O/C, correlate with the biochar properties that are relevant to the organic content such as polarity and aromaticity.<ref>{{cite journal|first1=Kyle|last1=Crombie|first2=Ond\u0159ej|last2=Ma\u0161ek|first3=Saran P.|last3=Sohi|first4=Peter|last4=Brownsort|first5=Andrew|last5=Cross|title=The effect of pyrolysis conditions on biochar stability as determined by three methods|journal=Global Change Biology Bioenergy|volume=5|issue=2|date=21 December 2012|pages=122\u2013131|issn=1757-1707|doi=10.1111/gcbb.12030|url=https://semanticscholar.org/paper/0ec89e2e9708bac309f62b920858d3e1fc747bf7}}</ref> The van-Krevelen diagram can be used to show the evolution of biochar atomic ratios in the production process.<ref>{{cite journal|first1=van|last1=Krevelen D.|title=Graphical-statistical method for the study of structure and reaction processes of coal|journal=Fuel|date=1950|volume=29|pages=269\u2013284|url=https://ci.nii.ac.jp/naid/10027945730/en/}}</ref> In the carbonization process, both the H/C and O/C ratio decreased due to the release of functional groups which contain hydrogen and oxygen.<ref>{{cite journal|first1=Kathrin|last1=Weber|first2=Peter|last2=Quicker|title=Properties of biochar|journal=Fuel|volume=217|date=1 April 2018|pages=240\u2013261|issn=0016-2361|doi=10.1016/j.fuel.2017.12.054}}</ref>\n\n== Uses ==\n\n=== Carbon sink ===\n{{See also|Climate engineering}}\n\nThe burning and natural decomposition of biomass releases large amounts of [[Carbon dioxide in Earth's atmosphere|carbon dioxide]] and [[methane]] to the Earth's [[Atmosphere of Earth|atmosphere]]. The biochar production process also releases CO2 (up to 50% of the biomass); however the remaining carbon content is stable indefinitely.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Woolf|first=Dominic|last2=Amonette|first2=James E.|last3=Street-Perrott|first3=F. Alayne|last4=Lehmann|first4=Johannes|last5=Joseph|first5=Stephen|date=2010-08-10|title=Sustainable biochar to mitigate global climate change|journal=Nature Communications|language=en|volume=1|issue=1|pages=1\u20139|doi=10.1038/ncomms1053|issn=2041-1723|pmc=2964457|pmid=20975722}}</ref>   Biochar presents a stable way of carbon storage in the ground for centuries, potentially reducing or stalling the growth in atmospheric [[greenhouse gas]] levels. Simultaneously, its presence in the earth can improve [[water quality]], increase [[soil fertility]], raise [[agricultural productivity]], and reduce pressure on [[old-growth forest]]s.<ref>{{harvnb|Laird|2008|pp=100, 178\u2013181}}</ref>\n\nBiochar can sequester carbon in the soil for hundreds to thousands of years, like [[coal]].<ref name=\"Terra Preta de Indio\">{{cite journal\n| url=http://www.css.cornell.edu/faculty/lehmann/research/terra%20preta/terrapretamain.html\n| title=Terra Preta de Indio\n| last=Lehmann |first=Johannes |journal=Soil Biochemistry (Internal Citations Omitted)}}  Not only do biochar-enriched soils contain more carbon - 150gC/kg compared to 20-30gC/kg in surrounding soils - but biochar-enriched soils are, on average, more than twice as deep as surrounding soils.{{Citation needed|date=August 2011}}</ref><ref>{{harvnb|Lehmann|2007b|PP=143}} \"this sequestration can be taken a step further by heating the plant biomass without oxygen (a process known as low-temperature pyrolysis).\"</ref><ref>{{harvnb|Lehmann|2007a|pp=381, 385}} \"pyrolysis produces 3\u20139 times more energy than is invested in generating the energy. At the same time, about half of the carbon can be sequestered in soil. The total carbon stored in these soils can be one order of magnitude higher than adjacent soils.</ref><ref>{{cite journal\n |journal      = [[New Zealand Science Review]]\n |url          = http://www.biochar-international.org/images/NZSR64_1_Winsley.pdf\n |title        = Biochar and Bioenergy Production for Climate Change Mitigation\n |last         = Winsley\n |first        = Peter\n |volume       = 64\n |issue        = 5\n |page         = 5\n |year         = 2007\n |access-date  = 10 July 2008\n |archive-url  = https://web.archive.org/web/20131004222126/http://www.biochar-international.org/images/NZSR64_1_Winsley.pdf\n |archive-date = 4 October 2013\n |url-status     = dead\n}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal\n| last1=Kern |first=Dirse C.\n| title=New Dark Earth Experiment in the Tailandia City \u2013 Para-Brazil: The Dream of Wim Sombroek |journal=18th World Congress of Soil Science |date=9\u201315 July 2006}}</ref> Such a carbon-negative technology would lead to a net withdrawal of CO<sub>2</sub> from the atmosphere, while producing consumable energy. This technique is advocated by prominent scientists such as [[James Hansen]], head of the [[Goddard Institute for Space Studies|NASA Goddard Institute for Space Studies]],<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.thestar.com/sciencetech/article/654444 | location=Toronto | work=The Star | title=Sole option is to adapt, climate author says | first=Tyler | last=Hamilton | date=22 June 2009}}</ref> and [[James Lovelock]], creator of the [[Gaia hypothesis]], for [[mitigation of global warming]] by [[greenhouse gas remediation]].<ref>{{harvnb|Vince|2009}}</ref>\n\nResearchers have estimated that sustainable use of biochar could reduce the global net emissions of carbon dioxide ({{chem|CO|2}}), [[methane]], and [[nitrous oxide]] by up to 1.8\u2009Pg [[Carbon dioxide equivalent|{{chem|CO|2}}-C equivalent]] ({{chem|CO|2}}-C<sub>e</sub>) per year (12% of current anthropogenic {{chem|CO|2}}-C<sub>e</sub> emissions), and total net emissions over the course of the next century by 130\u2009Pg {{chem|CO|2}}-C<sub>e</sub>, without endangering [[food security]], [[habitat]]s, or [[soil conservation]].<ref name=\"Sustainable biochar to mitigate global climate change\">{{cite journal\n |title=Sustainable biochar to mitigate global climate change\n  |journal=Nature Communications\n  |volume=1\n  |issue=5\n  |pages=1\u20139\n  |year=2010\n|doi=10.1038/ncomms1053\n  |pmid=20975722\n  |pmc=2964457\n  |last1=Woolf\n  |first1=Dominic\n  |last2=Amonette\n  |first2=James E.\n  |last3=Street-Perrott\n  |first3=F. Alayne\n  |last4=Lehmann\n  |first4=Johannes\n  |last5=Joseph\n  |first5=Stephen\n  |bibcode=2010NatCo...1...56W\n }}</ref>\n\n=== Soil amendment ===\n[[File:Biochar pile in tarp.jpg|alt=Biochar in a white tarp|thumb|Biochar in preparation as a soil amendment]]\nBiochar is recognized as offering a number of [[soil health]] benefits.  The extremely porous nature of biochar is found to be effective at retaining both water and water-soluble nutrients.  Soil biologist [[Elaine Ingham]] indicates<ref>Ingham, Elaine ''[https://web.archive.org/web/20150217052426/http://www.needfire.info/home/interview-with-dr-elaine-ingham Interview with Elaine Ingham]'', (2015)</ref> the extreme suitability of biochar as a habitat for many beneficial soil [[soil biology|micro organisms]].  She points out that when pre-charged with these beneficial organisms biochar becomes an extremely effective soil amendment promoting good soil and, in turn, plant health.\n\nBiochar has also been shown to reduce leaching of ''[[Escherichia coli|E-coli]]'' through sandy soils depending on application rate, feedstock, pyrolysis temperature, soil moisture content, soil texture, and surface properties of the bacteria.<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Bolster | first1 = C.H. | last2 = Abit | first2 = S.M. | year = 2012 | title = Biochar pyrolyzed at two temperatures affects Escherichia coli transport through a sandy soil | url = https://semanticscholar.org/paper/173e555b389ac0b849df55395ea57ceb4fc77a69| journal = Journal of Environmental Quality | volume = 41 | issue = 1| pages = 124\u2013133 | doi=10.2134/jeq2011.0207| pmid = 22218181 }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Abit | first1 = S.M. | last2 = Bolster | first2 = C.H. | last3 = Cai | first3 = P. | last4 = Walker | first4 = S.L. | year = 2012 | title = Influence of feedstock and pyrolysis temperature of biochar amendments on transport of Escherichia coli in saturated and unsaturated soil | journal =  Environmental Science & Technology| volume = 46 | issue = 15| pages = 8097\u20138105 | doi=10.1021/es300797z| pmid = 22738035 | bibcode = 2012EnST...46.8097A }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Abit | first1 = S.M. | last2 = Bolster | first2 = C.H. | last3 = Cantrell | first3 = K.B. | last4 = Flores | first4 = J.Q. | last5 = Walker | first5 = S.L. | year = 2014 | title = Transport of Escherichia coli, Salmonella typhimurium, and microspheres in biochar-amended soils with different textures | journal = Journal of Environmental Quality | volume = 43 | issue = 1| pages = 371\u2013378 | doi=10.2134/jeq2013.06.0236| pmid = 25602571 }}</ref>\n\nFor plants that require high [[potash]] and elevated [[pH]],<ref>Lehmann, Johannes, and Jose Pereira da Silva Jr., Christoph Steiner, Thomas Nehls, Wolfgang Zech, & Bruno Glaser, ''Nutrient availability and leaching in an archaeological Anthrosol and a Ferralsol of the Central Amazon basin: fertilizer, manure and charcoal amendments'', 249 Plant & Soil 343, 355 (2003)</ref> biochar can be used as a [[Soil conditioner|soil amendment]] to improve yield.\n\nBiochar can improve water quality, reduce soil emissions of [[greenhouse gases]], reduce [[leaching (agriculture)|nutrient leaching]], reduce [[soil acidity]], and reduce [[irrigation]] and [[fertilizer]] requirements.<ref>''Supra'' note 6; Day, Danny, Robert J. Evans, James W. Lee, and Don Reicosky, ''Economical {{chem|CO|2}}, {{chem|SO|x}}, and {{chem|NO|x}} capture from fossil-fuel utilization with combined renewable hydrogen production and large-scale carbon sequestration'', 30 Energy 2558, 2560</ref> Biochar was also found under certain circumstances to induce plant systemic responses to foliar fungal diseases and to improve plant responses to diseases caused by soilborne pathogens.<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Elad | first1 = Y. | last2 = Rav David | first2 = D. | last3 = Meller Harel | first3 = Y. | last4 = Borenshtein | first4 = M. | last5 = Kalifa Hananel | first5 = B. | last6 = Silber | first6 = A. | last7 = Graber | first7 = E.R. | year = 2010 | title = Induction of systemic resistance in plants by biochar, a soil-applied carbon sequestering agent | journal = Phytopathology | volume = 100 | issue = 9| pages = 913\u2013921 | doi=10.1094/phyto-100-9-0913| pmid = 20701489 }}</ref><ref>Meller Harel, Y., Elad, Y., Rav David, D., Borenstein, M., Schulcani, R., Lew, B., Graber, E.R. (2012) Biochar mediates systemic response of strawberry to foliar fungal pathogens. Plant and Soil, 357:245-257</ref><ref name=\"Jaiswal, A.K. 2014\">{{cite journal | last1 = Jaiswal | first1 = A.K. | last2 = Elad | first2 = Y. | last3 = Graber | first3 = E.R. | last4 = Frenkel | first4 = O. | year = 2014 | title = Rhizoctonia solani suppression and plant growth promotion in cucumber as affected by biochar pyrolysis temperature, feedstock and concentration | journal = Soil Biology and Biochemistry | volume = 69 | pages = 110\u2013118 | doi=10.1016/j.soilbio.2013.10.051}}</ref>\n\nThe various impacts of biochar can be dependent on the properties of the biochar,<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Silber | first1 = A. | last2 = Levkovitch | first2 = I. | last3 = Graber | first3 = E. R. | year = 2010 | title = pH-dependent mineral release and surface properties of cornstraw biochar: Agronomic implications | url = https://figshare.com/articles/pH_Dependent_Mineral_Release_and_Surface_Properties_of_Cornstraw_Biochar_Agronomic_Implications/2704741| journal = Environmental Science & Technology| volume = 44 | issue = 24| pages = 9318\u20139323 | doi=10.1021/es101283d| pmid = 21090742 | bibcode = 2010EnST...44.9318S }}</ref> as well as the amount applied,<ref name=\"Jaiswal, A.K. 2014\"/> and there is still a lack of knowledge about the important mechanisms and properties.<ref>{{harvnb|Glaser|Lehmann|Zech|2002|pp=224 note 7}} \"Three main factors influence the properties of charcoal: (1) the type of organic matter used for charring, (2) the charring environment (e.g. temperature, air), and (3) additions during the charring process. The source of charcoal material strongly influences the direct effects of charcoal amendments on nutrient contents and availability.\"</ref> Biochar impact may depend on regional conditions including soil type, soil condition (depleted or healthy), temperature, and humidity.<ref>Dr. Wardle points out that improved plant growth has been observed in tropical (depleted) soils by referencing Lehmann, but that in the boreal (high native [[soil organic matter]] content) forest this experiment was run in, it accelerated the native soil organic matter loss. Wardle, ''supra'' note 18. (\"Although several studies have recognized the potential of black C for enhancing ecosystem carbon sequestration, our results show that these effects can be partially offset by its capacity to stimulate loss of native soil C, at least for boreal forests.\") (internal citations omitted) (emphasis added).</ref> Modest additions of biochar to soil reduce [[nitrous oxide]] {{chem|N|2|O}}<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://sior.ub.edu/jspui/cris/socialimpact/socialimpact00542|title=Biochar decreased N2O emissions from soils. [Social Impact]. FERTIPLUS. Reducing mineral fertilisers and agro-chemicals by recycling treated organic waste as compost and biochar products (2011-2015). Framework Programme 7 (FP7).|website=SIOR, Social Impact Open Repository|access-date=|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170905182752/http://sior.ub.edu/jspui/cris/socialimpact/socialimpact00542|archive-date=5 September 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref> emissions by up to 80% and eliminate [[methane]] emissions, which are both more potent greenhouse gases than {{co2}}.<ref>{{harvnb|Lehmann|2007a|pp=note 3 at 384}} \"In greenhouse experiments, NO<sub>x</sub> emissions were reduced by 80% and methane emissions were completely suppressed with biochar additions of 20 g kg-1 (2%) to a forage grass stand.\"</ref>\n\n<!--Unrelated to the next passage, unless rewrite it with the addition of conjunction: Pollutants, such as metals and [[pesticide]]s, seep into soil and contaminate food supplies, reducing the amount of land suitable for agricultural production. -->Studies have reported positive effects from biochar on crop production in degraded and nutrient\u2013poor soils.<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.csiro.au/resources/Biochar-Factsheet.html|title= Biochar fact sheet|publisher=csiro.au|accessdate=2 September 2016}}</ref> The application of compost and biochar under FP7 project FERTIPLUS has had positive effects in soil humidity, and crop productivity and quality in different countries.<ref name=\"socialimpact00544\">{{Cite web|url=http://sior.ub.edu/jspui/cris/socialimpact/socialimpact00544|title=Improvement of soil quality. [Social Impact]. FERTIPLUS. Reducing mineral fertilisers and agro-chemicals by recycling treated organic waste as compost and biochar products (2011-2015). Framework Programme 7 (FP7).|website=SIOR. Social Impact Open Repository|access-date=|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170905190513/http://sior.ub.edu/jspui/cris/socialimpact/socialimpact00544|archive-date=5 September 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref> Biochar can be designed with specific qualities to target distinct properties of soils.<ref>Novak, Jeff. Development of Designer Biochar to Remediate Specific Chemical and Physical Aspects of Degraded Soils. Proc. of North American Biochar Conference 2009, University of Colorado at Boulder. Florence: U.S. Department of Agriculture, 2009. 1-16. Print</ref> In a Colombian savanna soil, biochar reduced leaching of critical nutrients, created a higher crop uptake of nutrients, and provided greater soil availability of nutrients.<ref>Julie, Major, Johannes Lehmann, Macro Rondon, and Susan J. Riha. Nutrient Leaching below the Rooting Zone Is Reduced by Biochar, the Hydrology of a Colombian Savanna Oxisol Is Unaffected. Proc. of North American Biochar Conference 2009, University of Colorado at Boulder. Ithaca: Cornell University Department of Crop and Soil Sciences, 2009. Print.</ref> At 10% levels biochar reduced contaminant levels in plants by up to 80%, while reducing total [[chlordane]] and [[DDX (chemistry)|DDX]] content in the plants by 68 and 79%, respectively.<ref>Elmer, Wade, Jason C. White, and Joseph J. Pignatello. Impact of Biochar Addition to Soil on the Bioavailability of Chemicals Important in Agriculture. Rep. New Haven: University of Connecticut, 2009. Print.</ref> On the other hand, because of its high adsorption capacity, biochar may reduce the efficacy of soil applied pesticides that are needed for weed and pest control.<ref name=\"Graber, E.R. 2011\">Graber, E.R., Tsechansky, L., Gerstl, Z., Lew, B. (2011) High surface area biochar negatively impacts herbicide efficacy. Plant and Soil, 353:95-106</ref><ref>Graber, E.R., Tsechansky, L., Khanukov, J., Oka, Y. (2011) Sorption, volatilization and efficacy of the fumigant 1,3-dichloropropene in a biochar-amended soil. Soil Science Society of America Journal. 75(4) 1365-1373</ref> High-surface-area biochars may be particularly problematic in this regard; more research into the long-term effects of biochar addition to soil is needed.<ref name=\"Graber, E.R. 2011\"/>\n\n=== Slash-and-char ===\n\nSwitching from ''[[slash-and-burn]]'' to ''[[slash-and-char]]'' farming techniques in Brazil can decrease both deforestation of the [[Amazon basin]] and carbon dioxide emission, as well as increase crop yields. Slash-and-burn leaves only 3% of the carbon from the organic material in the soil.<ref>{{harvnb|Glaser|Lehmann|Zech|2002|pp=note 7 at 225}} \"The published data average at about 3% charcoal formation of the original biomass C.\"</ref>\n\nSlash-and-char can keep up to 50% of the carbon in a highly stable form.<ref>''Biochar Sequestration in Terrestrial Ecosystems \u2013 A Review'', by Johannes Lehmann, John Gaunt, and Marco Rondon. Mitigation and Adaptation Strategies for Global change 403, 404 (2006). ''supra'' note 11 at 407 (\"If this woody above ground biomass were converted into biochar by means of simple kiln techniques and applied to soil, more than 50% of this carbon would be sequestered in a highly stable form.\")</ref> Returning the biochar into the soil rather than removing it all for energy production reduces the need for nitrogen fertilizers, thereby reducing cost and emissions from fertilizer production and transport.<ref>{{harvnb|Gaunt|Lehmann|2008|pp=4152}} note 3 (\"This results in increased crop yields in low-input agriculture and increased crop yield per unit of fertilizer applied (fertilizer efficiency) in [[Intensive farming|high-input agriculture]] as well as reductions in off-site effects such as runoff, erosion, and gaseous losses.\")</ref> Additionally, by improving the soil's ability to be tilled, its fertility and its productivity, biochar-enhanced soils can indefinitely sustain agricultural production, whereas non-enriched soils quickly become depleted of nutrients, forcing farmers to abandon the fields, producing a continuous slash and burn cycle and the continued loss of [[tropical rainforest]]. Using pyrolysis to produce bio-energy also has the added benefit of not requiring infrastructure changes the way processing biomass for [[cellulosic ethanol]] does. Additionally, the biochar produced can be applied by the currently used machinery for tilling the soil or equipment used to apply fertilizer.<ref>{{harvnb|Lehmann|2007b|pp=note 9 at 143}} \"It can be mixed with manures or fertilizers and included in no-tillage methods, without the need for additional equipment.\"</ref>\n\n=== Water retention ===\n\nBiochar is [[hygroscopic]]. Thus it is a desirable soil material in many locations due to its ability to attract and retain water. This is possible because of its [[porosity|porous structure]] and high [[specific surface area]].<ref>[https://www.agronomy.org/files/students/2010-ricigliano-entry.pdf Terra Pretas: Charcoal Amendments Influence on Relict Soils and Modern Agriculture]</ref> As a result, nutrients such as [[phosphate]], and [[agrochemical]]s are retained for the plants benefit. Plants are therefore healthier, and less [[fertilizer]] leaches into [[Surface water|surface]] or [[groundwater]].\n\n=== Energy production: bio-oil and syngas ===\n{{main|Biofuel}}\nMobile pyrolysis units can be used to lower the costs of transportation of the biomass if the biochar is returned to the soil and the syngas stream is used to power the process.<ref>{{harvnb|Badger|Fransham|2006|pp= 322}}</ref><ref>Michael Jacobson, Cedric Briens and Franco Berruti, \"Lift tube technology for increasing heat transfer in an annular pyrolysis reactor\", CFB\u20199, Hamburg, Germany, 13\u201316 May 2008.</ref> Bio-oil contains organic acids that are corrosive to steel containers, has a high water vapor content that is detrimental to ignition, and, unless carefully cleaned, contains some biochar particles which can block injectors.<ref>Yaman, Serdar, ''pyrolysis of biomass to produce fuels and chemical feedstocks'', 45 Energy Conversion & MGMT 651, 659 (2003).</ref> Currently, it is less suitable for use as a kind of [[biodiesel]] than other sources.\n\nIf biochar is used for the production of energy rather than as a soil amendment, it can be directly substituted for any application that uses coal. Pyrolysis also may be the most cost-effective way of [[electricity generation]] from biomaterial.<ref>Bridgwater, A. V., A.J. Toft, and J.G. Brammer, ''A techno-economic comparison of power production by biomass fast pyrolysis with gasification and combustion'', 6 Renewable & Sustainable Energy Rev. 181, 231 (\"the fast pyrolysis and diesel engine system is clearly the most economic of the novel systems at scales up to 15 MWe\")</ref>\n\n=== Stock fodder ===\nA [[West Australia]]n farmer has explored the use of biochar mixed with [[molasses]] as stock [[fodder]]. He asserts that in [[ruminant]]s, biochar can assist digestion and reduce [[Methane#Ruminants|methane production]]. The farmer also uses [[dung beetle]]s to work the biochar infused dung down into the soil without using machinery. It is proposed that the nitrogen and carbon in the dung are both incorporated into the soil rather than staying on the soil surface, reducing the production of [[Nitrous oxide#Greenhouse effect|nitrous oxide]] and [[Carbon dioxide#In Earth's atmosphere|carbon dioxide]], which are both greenhouse gasses. The nitrogen and carbon then both add to soil fertility. There is also on-farm evidence that the fodder has led to improvements of liveweight gain in [[Angus cattle|Angus-cross cattle]].<ref name=\"abc.net.au-2019-10-18-beetles-charcoal\">{{cite web\n | url =https://www.abc.net.au/news/rural/2019-10-18/wa-farmer-uses-beetles-and-charcoal-to-combat-climate-change/11613846\n | title =Poo-eating beetles and charcoal used by WA farmer to combat climate change\n | last =Daly\n | first =Jon\n | date =18 October 2019\n | website =ABC.net.au\n | publisher =Australian Broadcasting Corporation\n | access-date =18 October 2019\n | quote =Mr Pow said his innovative farming system could help livestock producers become more profitable while helping to address the impact of climate change. }}</ref>\n\nDoug Pow won the Australian Government Innovation in Agriculture Land Management Award at the 2019 Western Australian [[Landcare in Australia|Landcare]] Awards for this innovation.<ref name=\"landcareawards2019\">{{cite web\n | url =https://landcareaustralia.org.au/landcareawards2019\n | title =2019 State & Territory Landcare Awards Celebrate Outstanding Landcare Champions\n | date =2019\n | website =Landcare Australia\n | publisher =Landcare Australia\n | access-date =18 October 2019\n }}</ref><ref name=\"abc.net.au-2019-10-18-beetles-charcoal\" /> Mr Pow's work led to two further trials on dairy cattle, with the results of odour reduction and increased milk production.<ref>{{cite web\n | url =https://landcareaustralia.org.au/news/manjimup-farmer-employing-dung-beetle-to-tackle-climate-change-set-to-represent-wa-on-national-stage/\n | title =Manjimup farmer employing dung beetle to tackle climate-change set to represent WA on national stage\n | date =October 2019\n | website =Landcare Australia\n | publisher =Landcare Australia\n | access-date =18 October 2019\n }}</ref>\n\n== Direct and indirect benefits ==\n<!--This section should be merged into above sections:-->\n* The pyrolysis of forest- or agriculture-derived biomass residue generates a biofuel without competition with crop production.\n* Biochar is a pyrolysis byproduct that may be ploughed into soils in crop fields to enhance their fertility and stability, and for medium- to long-term carbon sequestration in these soils. It has meant a remarkable improvement in tropical soils showing positive effects in increasing soil fertility and in improving disease resistance in West European Soils.<ref name=\"socialimpact00544\" />\n* Biochar enhances the natural process: the biosphere captures {{chem|CO|2}}, especially through plant production, but only a small portion is stably sequestered for a relatively long time (soil, wood, etc.).\n* Biomass production to obtain biofuels and biochar for carbon sequestration in the soil is a carbon-negative process, i.e. more {{chem|CO|2}} is removed from the atmosphere than released, thus enabling long-term sequestration.<ref>Cornet A., Escadafal R., 2009. Is biochar \"green\"? CSFD Viewpoint. Montpellier, France. 8 pp.</ref>\n\n== Research ==\n\nResearch into aspects involving pyrolysis/biochar is underway around the world. From 2005 to 2012, there were 1,038 articles that included the word \"biochar\" or \"bio-char\" in the topic that had been indexed in the ISI Web of Science.<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Verheijen | first1 = F.G.A. | last2 = Graber | first2 = E.R. | last3 = Ameloot | first3 = N. | last4 = Bastos | first4 = A.C. | last5 = Sohi | first5 = S. | last6 = Knicker | first6 = H. | year = 2014 | title = Biochars in soils: new insights and emerging research needs | journal = Eur. J. Soil Science | volume = 65 | pages = 22\u201327 | doi = 10.1111/ejss.12127 | hdl = 10261/93245 }}</ref> Further research is in progress by such diverse institutions around the world as [[Cornell University]], the [[University of Edinburgh]] (which has a dedicated research unit),<ref>https://www.ed.ac.uk/geosciences/facilities/biochar</ref> the University of Georgia,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2009/TECH/science/03/30/biochar.warming.energy/index.html#cnnSTCVideo|title=''Can Biochar save the planet?''|publisher=CNN|accessdate=10 March 2009}}</ref><ref>Merrit, A.C. (2017) \"Biochar nearly doubles peanut yield in student\u2019s research\",  http://ftfpeanutlab.caes.uga.edu/news-and-events/news/biochar-nearly-doubles-peanut-yield-in-students-research.html Published 29 June 2017</ref> the [[Volcani Institute of Agricultural Research|Agricultural Research Organization (ARO) of Israel, Volcani Center]],<ref>[https://sites.google.com/site/ibrnisraelbiocharnetwork/]</ref> and the [[University of Delaware]].\n\nLong-term effect of biochar on soil C sequestration of recent carbon inputs has been examined using soil from arable fields in Belgium with charcoal-enriched black spots dating >150 years ago from historical charcoal production mound kilns. [[Topsoil]]s from these 'black spots' had a higher organic C concentration [3.6 \u00b1 0.9% organic carbon (OC)] than adjacent soils outside these black spots (2.1 \u00b1 0.2% OC). The soils had been cropped with maize for at least 12 years which provided a continuous input of C with a C isotope signature (\u03b413C) \u221213.1, distinct from the \u03b413C of soil organic carbon (\u221227.4 \u2030) and charcoal (\u221225.7 \u2030) collected in the surrounding area. The isotope signatures in the soil revealed that maize-derived C concentration was significantly higher in charcoal-amended samples ('black spots') than in adjacent unamended ones (0.44% vs. 0.31%; P = 0.02). Topsoils were subsequently collected as a gradient across two 'black spots' along with corresponding adjacent soils outside these black spots and soil respiration, and physical soil fractionation was conducted. Total soil respiration (130 days) was unaffected by charcoal, but the maize-derived C respiration per unit maize-derived OC in soil significantly decreased about half (P < 0.02) with increasing charcoal-derived C in soil. Maize-derived C was proportionally present more in protected soil aggregates in the presence of charcoal. The lower specific mineralization and increased C sequestration of recent C with charcoal are attributed to a combination of physical protection, C saturation of microbial communities and, potentially, slightly higher annual primary production. Overall, this study provides evidence of the capacity of biochar to enhance C sequestration in soils through reduced C turnover on the long term. ([http://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/10.1111/gcbb.12250/full Hernandez-Soriano ''et al'', 2015]).\n\nBiochar sequesters carbon (C) in soils because of its prolonged residence time, ranging from several years to millennia. In addition, biochar can promote indirect C-sequestration by increasing crop yield while, potentially, reducing C-mineralization. Laboratory studies have evidenced effects of biochar on C-mineralization using 13C isotope signatures. [http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0048969715312614 (Kerre et al, 2016)]\n\nFluorescence analysis of the dissolved organic matter from soil amended with biochar revealed that biochar application increased a humic-like fluorescent component, likely associated with biochar-carbon in solution. The combined spectroscopy-microscopy approach revealed the accumulation of aromatic-carbon in discrete spots in the solid-phase of microaggregates and its co-localization with clay minerals for soil amended with raw residue or biochar. The co-localization of aromatic-C:polysaccharides-C was consistently reduced upon biochar application. These finding suggested that reduced C metabolism is an important mechanism for C stabilization in biochar-amended soils [https://www.nature.com/articles/srep25127 (Hernandez-Soriano ''et al'', 2016)]\n\nStudents at [[Stevens Institute of Technology]] in New Jersey are developing [[supercapacitor]]s that use electrodes made of biochar.<ref name=Supercapacitors>{{cite web\n  |title=A Cheaper, Greener Material for Supercapacitors\n  |url=http://www.solarnovus.com/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=2859:a-cheaper-greener-material-for-supercapacitors&catid=52:applications-tech-research&Itemid=247\n  |publisher=[[Stevens Institute of Technology]]\n  |year=2011\n  |accessdate=25 May 2011\n}}</ref> A process developed by [[University of Florida]] researchers that removes [[phosphate]] from water, also yields [[methane gas]] usable as fuel and phosphate-laden carbon suitable for enriching soil.<ref name=\"Removing Phosphate from Water\">{{cite web\n  |title=Biochar\" More Effective, Cheaper at Removing Phosphate from Water\n  |url=http://eponline.com/articles/2011/05/18/biochar-more-effective-cheaper-at-removing-phosphate-from-water.aspx\n  |publisher=[[University of Florida]]\n  |year=2011\n  |accessdate=18 May 2011\n}}</ref> \nResearchers at the University of Auckland are also working on utilizing biochar in concrete applications to reduce carbon emissions during concrete production and to improve the strength considerably.<ref>Akhtar, A., & Sarmah, A. K. (2018). Strength improvement of recycled aggregate concrete through silicon rich char derived from organic waste. Journal of Cleaner Production, 196, 411\u2013423.</ref> It has also demonstrated that the biochar can be used as a suitable filler in polymer matrix.<ref>Anesh Manjaly Poulose,Ahmed Yagoub Elnour, Arfat Anis, Hamid Shaikh, S.M.Al-Zahrani, Justin George, Mohammad I.Al-Wabel, Adel R.Usman, Yong Sik Ok, Daniel C.W.Tsang, Ajit K.Sarmah (2018).Date palm biochar-polymer composites: An investigation of electrical, mechanical, thermal and rheological characteristics.Science of the Total Environment,Volumes 619\u2013620, 1 April 2018, Pages 311-318.</ref> Recently, biochar-starch bio-composites were prepared and its nano-mechanical behaviours were investigated using advanced dynamic atomic force microscopy.<ref>Justin Georgea, Lal B. Azadb, Anesh M. Poulosec, Yiran And, Ajit K. Sarmaha (2019).Nano-mechanical behaviour of biochar-starch polymer composite: Investigation through advanced dynamic atomic force microscopy.Composites Part A: Applied Science and Manufacturing,Volume 124, September 2019, 105486.</ref>\n\n== Possible commercial sector ==\nIf biomass is pyrolyzed to biochar and put back into the soil, rather than being completely burned, this may reduce carbon emissions. Potentially, the bioenergy industry might even be made to sequester net carbon.{{sfn|Lehmann|2007b|pp=143, 144}} Pyrolysis might be cost-effective for a combination of sequestration and energy production when the cost of a {{chem|CO|2}} ton reaches $37.{{sfn|Lehmann|2007b|pp=143, 144}} [[Carbon credit]]s could help to make implementation easier as most large biomass power producers are neither equipped to create biochar nor are financially motivated for making it (because implementing biochar production would leave less energy for power production).<ref name=\"renewableenergyworld.com\"/><ref>[http://biochar-us.org/biochar-and-renewable-energy-biomass Carbon Credits for Clean Energy and Sequestration]</ref>\n\nCurrent biochar projects make no significant impact on the overall global carbon budget, although expansion of this technique has been advocated as a [[climate engineering|geoengineering]] approach.<ref>[https://www.newscientist.com/article/dn14851 Ananthaswamy, Anil, ''Microwave factory to act as carbon sink'', ''New Scientist'', 1 October (2008) (\"Retrieved on 12 December 2008)]<br/>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/science/nature/7924373.stm ''Biochar: Is the hype justified?''] By Roger Harrabin - Environment analyst, (09:20 GMT, Monday, 16 March 2009) BBC News</ref> In May 2009, the Biochar Fund, a small \"social profit organization\", received a grant from the [[Congo Basin Forest Fund]] for a project in [[Central Africa]] to simultaneously slow down [[deforestation]], increase the [[food security]] of rural communities, provide [[renewable energy]] and sequester carbon. Though some farmers did report better maize crops, the project ended early without significant results and with promises to the farmers not kept.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.biofuelwatch.org.uk/wp-content/uploads/Biochar-Cameroon-report1.pdf |title=Biochar Fund Trials in Cameroon: Hype and Unfulfilled Promises |author=Benoit Anthony Ndameu |date=November 2011 |publisher=[[Biofuelwatch]] |accessdate=19 October 2012}}</ref>\n\nApplication rates of {{convert|2.5|-|20|tonne/ha}} appear to be required to produce significant improvements in plant yields. Biochar costs in developed countries vary from $300\u20137000/tonne, generally too high for the farmer/horticulturalist and prohibitive for low-input field crops. In developing countries, constraints on agricultural biochar relate more to biomass availability and production time. An alternative is to use small amounts of biochar in lower cost biochar-fertilizer complexes.<ref>Joseph, S., Graber, E.R., Chia, C., Munroe, P., Donne, S., Thomas, T., Nielsen, S., Marjo, C., Rutlidge, H., Pan, GX., Li, L., Taylor, P., Rawal, A., Hook, J. (2013). Shifting Paradigms on Biochar: Micro/Nano-structures and Soluble Components are Responsible for its Plant-Growth Promoting Ability. Carbon Management 4:323-343</ref>\n\nVarious companies in [[North America]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://biochar.us|title=Soils booster for your garden by Biochar - Naturagain|website=BioChar.us|language=en-US|access-date=2018-01-25}}</ref> [[Australia]], and [[England]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://biochar.co.uk|title=Soils booster for your garden by Biochar - Naturagain|website=BioChar.co.uk|language=en-US|access-date=2018-01-25}}</ref> sell biochar or biochar production units. In Sweden the 'Stockholm Solution' is an urban tree planting system that uses 30% biochar to support healthy growth of the urban forest.<ref>{{cite news|last1=O'Sullivan|first1=Feargus|title=Stockholm's Ingenious Plan to Recycle Yard Waste|date=20 December 2016|url=https://www.citylab.com/solutions/2016/12/stockholm-throw-out-old-christmas-trees-biochar-environment/511196/|website=Citylab|accessdate=15 March 2018}}</ref> The Qatar Aspire Park now uses biochar to help trees cope with the intense heat of their summers{{Citation needed|date=June 2019|reason=Carbon sequestration is of large interest due to climate change and all ongoing efforts should be well documented to back the credibility of this method.}}.\n\nAt the 2009 International Biochar Conference, a mobile pyrolysis unit with a specified intake of {{convert|1000|lb}} was introduced for agricultural applications. The unit had a length of 12 feet and height of 7 feet (3.6 m by 2.1m).<ref name='biomassmag.com/article_id=3091'>{{cite news\n| first=Anna\n| last=Austin\n| title=A New Climate Change Mitigation Tool\n| date=October 2009\n| publisher=BBI International\n| url =http://www.biomassmagazine.com/article.jsp?article_id=3091&q=&page=all\n| work =Biomass Magazine\n| accessdate = 30 October 2009}}</ref>\n\nA production unit in [[Dunlap, Tennessee]] by [[Mantria Corporation Ponzi scheme|Mantria Corporation]] opened in August 2009 after testing and an initial run, was later shut down as part of a [[Ponzi scheme]] investigation.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://philadelphia.bizjournals.com/philadelphia/stories/2009/11/16/daily25.html | work=[[Philadelphia Business Journal]] | first=Jeff | last=Blumenthal | title=Wragg, Knorr ordered to halt Mantria operations | date=17 November 2009}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n{{Portal|Ecology}}\n* [[Activated carbon]]\n* [[Charring]]\n* [[Pellet fuel]]\n* [[Soil carbon]]\n* [[Soil ecology]]\n\n== Notes ==\n{{Reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n== References ==\n\n* {{cite journal| first1= Tevfik|last1= Aysu|first2= M. Ma\u015fuk|last2= K\u00fc\u00e7\u00fck|title= Biomass pyrolysis in a fixed-bed reactor: Effects of pyrolysis parameters on product yields and characterization of products|journal= Energy|volume= 64|issue =1|date= 16 December 2013|pages= 1002\u20131025|issn=0360-5442|doi= 10.1016/j.energy.2013.11.053}}\n* {{cite journal\n| last1=Badger |first1=Phillip C. |first2=Peter |last2=Fransham\n| title=Use of mobile fast pyrolysis plants to densify biomass and reduce biomass handling costs\u2014A preliminary assessment\n| volume=30 |issue=4 |pages=321\u2013325 |journal=Biomass & Bioenergy  |year=2006 |ref=harv|doi=10.1016/j.biombioe.2005.07.011 }}\n\n* {{cite journal|last=Biederman|first=Lori A.|author2=W. Stanley Harpole|title=Biochar and Managed Perennial Ecosystems|journal=Iowa State Research Farm Progress Reports|year=2011|url=http://lib.dr.iastate.edu/farms_reports/136/|accessdate=12 February 2013}}\n* {{cite thesis|type=dissertation|last=Brewer|first=Catherine|title=Biochar Characterization and Engineering|publisher=Iowa State University|year=2012|url=http://lib.dr.iastate.edu/etd/12284/|accessdate=12 February 2013}}\n* {{cite journal|first1=Kyle|last1=Crombie|first2=Ond\u0159ej|last2=Ma\u0161ek|first3=Saran P.|last3=Sohi|first4=Peter|last4=Brownsort|first5=Andrew|last5=